</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D82E29A1E2887B09A739E59B64428123" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="83C53321FD4C1C1A0D43B4A0153A4043" pageId="28" pageNumber="59">Type locality. Southern coast of eastern United States.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3C45EE097FAFCA59FB251CA80E788D37" pageId="28" pageNumber="59">Distribution. Black Sea Basin, Caspian Sea, coasts of western Europe, Caribbean, and northern South America.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="45E8E71E099D19A5A8384E21D3AEECAB" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="CBBFEF51E8490657540F67DB4FEB572D" lastPageId="29" lastPageNumber="60" pageId="28" pageNumber="59">
Remarks. The species, native to the southern coast of North America, was first introduced in Europe in 1835 (
<bibRefCitation id="F1A73F7937AC2CF03B4A3C197A6893F8" author="Heiler, KCM" journalOrPublisher="Malacologia" pageId="76" pageNumber="107" pagination="185 - 192" title="A New Invasion Into an Ancient Lake - The Invasion History of the Dreissenid Mussel Mytilopsisleucophaeata (Conrad, 1831) and Its First Record in the Caspian Sea." url="https://doi.org/10.4002/040.053.0112" volume="53" year="2010">Heiler et al. 2010</bibRefCitation>
). In the Pontocaspian region, it first 
<pageBreakToken id="3E26D50B9DC46834B2763D8513961059" pageId="29" pageNumber="60" start="start">appeared</pageBreakToken>
in the northern Black Sea Basin in 2002 and was first collected in the Caspian Sea in 2009 (
<bibRefCitation id="598A6BDB0A7C75C03573FC7C0024B735" author="Heiler, KCM" journalOrPublisher="Malacologia" pageId="76" pageNumber="107" pagination="185 - 192" title="A New Invasion Into an Ancient Lake - The Invasion History of the Dreissenid Mussel Mytilopsisleucophaeata (Conrad, 1831) and Its First Record in the Caspian Sea." url="https://doi.org/10.4002/040.053.0112" volume="53" year="2010">Heiler et al. 2010</bibRefCitation>
). It is easily distinguished from Pontocaspian dreissenids by the presence of an aphophysis near the hinge.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
